title: A Single-Center, Randomized, Adaptive, Investigator/Subject Blind, Single Ascending Dose, Placebo-Controlled Phase I Study to Investigate the Safety, Tolerability, Immunogenicity and Pharmacokinetics of Intravenously Administered RO7126209 in Healthy Participants
description_brief: Study BP41192 is a randomized, adaptive, placebo-controlled parallel group study to investigate the safety, tolerability, immunogenicity and pharmacokinetics of single-ascending intravenous (IV) doses of RO7126209 in healthy participants. RO7126209 is being developed for the treatment of Alzheimer's Disease.
description_detailed: This study uses a parallel group design, with participants recruited in 5 planned sequential cohorts. Additional cohort(s) may be added if dose escalation stopping criteria are not met after cohort 5. Participants will receive a single IV dose of either RO7126209 or placebo. RO7126209 doses will be administered in ascending order. After the starting dose, subsequent doses will be selected in an adaptive manner during study conduct based on emerging safety, tolerability and PK data.

participantFlowModule.preAssignmentDetails: A total of 36 participants were enrolled at 1 site in the US, out of which 26 participants received active treatment while 10 received placebo.
participantFlowModule.recruitmentDetails: The study was conducted at 1 center in 1 country.

outcomeMeasures.description: An Adverse Event (AE) is any untoward medical occurrence in a participant administered a pharmaceutical product and which does not necessarily have to have a causal relationship with the treatment. An Adverse Event can therefore be any unfavorable and unintended sign (including abnormal laboratory values or abnormal clinical test results), symptom, or disease temporally associated with the use of a pharmaceutical product, whether or not considered related to the pharmaceutical product. Preexisting conditions which worsen during a study are also considered as Adverse Events.
outcomeMeasures.populationDescription: The Safety Population was defined as all participants randomised to study treatment and who received at least one dose of the study treatment, whether prematurely withdrawn from the study or not.

drug: RO7126209 (trontinemab) — a bispecific monoclonal antibody engineered to bind Aβ (amyloid‑beta) and the transferrin receptor (brain‑shuttle) to increase BBB penetration
explanation_target: Reason: The investigational product RO7126209 is described in the trial record as being developed for Alzheimer’s disease and administered IV in a phase 1 study. citeturn0search0turn0search2

Act: External sources identify RO7126209 as trontinemab, a bispecific monoclonal antibody that binds amyloid‑beta plaques and a transferrin receptor arm to enhance brain uptake (Roche 'brain‑shuttle' approach), i.e., an anti‑amyloid immunotherapy. citeturn0search6turn0search4

Reflect: This is a biologic targeting Alzheimer’s pathology (amyloid), so it fits the defined category 'disease‑targeted biologic' rather than a small molecule, cognitive enhancer, or symptom‑management therapy. The trial also uses placebo control and healthy volunteers for IV single‑ascending doses, consistent with early safety testing of a monoclonal antibody. citeturn0search2turn0search5

Web search sources used: Roche trial listing and clinical trial record (NCT04023994) describing the study; Alzforum and an MDPI review identifying RO7126209 as trontinemab and describing its bispecific anti‑Aβ / transferrin receptor design. citeturn0search0turn0search2turn0search6turn0search4
explanation_agent: Reason: The investigational product RO7126209 (trontinemab) is a bispecific monoclonal antibody engineered to bind amyloid‑beta (Aβ) and a transferrin receptor 'brain‑shuttle' arm to enhance blood–brain barrier uptake—i.e., an anti‑amyloid immunotherapy being developed for Alzheimer’s disease. citeturn0search1turn0search4

Act: Given the explicit Aβ binding mechanism described in trial records and company literature, the most specific CADRO match is A) Amyloid beta. Trial listings and phase‑I records identify RO7126209/trontinemab as an anti‑amyloid bispecific antibody. citeturn0search2turn0search0

Reflect: This classification is consistent with the drug’s design and development intent (disease‑targeted biologic that targets amyloid pathology). Although the molecule also engages the transferrin receptor to improve brain delivery, that is a delivery/transport mechanism rather than a separate pathogenic target—so the primary CADRO category remains A) Amyloid beta rather than Multi‑target. citeturn0search4turn0search1

Web sources used (most relevant): 1) Alzforum therapeutic page for trontinemab (describes bispecific anti‑Aβ/transferrin receptor design and phase data). citeturn0search1 2) ICH GCP / trial registry entry for the single ascending dose Phase I study (RO7126209 / trontinemab). citeturn0search2 3) Roche/Genentech press materials describing trontinemab (RO7126209) and amyloid PET results. citeturn0search4 4) ClinicalTrials summary listing for RO7126209 (Brainshuttle AD and related studies). citeturn0search0 5) Reuters summary reporting Roche’s development plans for trontinemab and its BBB‑shuttle design. citeturn0news12
